WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.080
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History

00:00:07.080 --> 00:00:08.080
and Culture.

00:00:08.080 --> 00:00:13.840
Today is the 26th of June 2016.

00:00:13.840 --> 00:00:17.960
This is David Klein from the History Department at Virginia Tech and also working with the

00:00:17.960 --> 00:00:22.640
Southern Oural History Program at the University of North Carolina Chapel Hill.

00:00:22.640 --> 00:00:27.560
We are working on the Civil Rights History Project today of the Library of Congress and the

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:31.880
Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:31.880 --> 00:00:35.880
Behind the camera we have Guha Shankar from the Library of Congress and John Bishop

00:00:35.880 --> 00:00:38.800
of Media Generation and UCLA.

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:44.400
And we are so honored to be at the home of Michael McCarty today in Los Angeles.

00:00:44.400 --> 00:00:48.840
And if you could introduce yourself for the tape, we'd appreciate it.

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:51.560
Michael Demacardi, Storyteller, How about?

00:00:51.560 --> 00:00:53.880
We'll run it.

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:56.040
And Michael, where and when were you born?

00:00:56.040 --> 00:00:58.600
Chicago Eleanor, September 7th, 1950.

00:00:58.600 --> 00:00:59.600
Okay.

00:00:59.600 --> 00:01:00.600
Fantastic.

00:01:00.600 --> 00:01:06.200
So let's start with your childhood and your family and tell us a little bit about your

00:01:06.200 --> 00:01:08.240
people and where you came up.

00:01:08.240 --> 00:01:11.000
I grew up in a West Side of Chicago.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:12.400
I was born in the South Side.

00:01:12.400 --> 00:01:16.240
We moved to the West Side when I was about three years old.

00:01:16.240 --> 00:01:22.960
And the greatest influence in my life, I like to say, is my mom.

00:01:22.960 --> 00:01:26.760
I am a reedaholic because of my mom.

00:01:26.760 --> 00:01:31.960
I can remember my mom reading me and telling me stories from the time I was about two years

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:33.760
old.

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:39.760
And we always had books and my mother used to say, if you can read, you can do anything.

00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:45.840
And the other thing, interestingly enough that she instilled in me is the idea that if

00:01:45.840 --> 00:01:52.920
you saw something wrong, you had an obligation to do something about it or to let something

00:01:52.920 --> 00:01:55.400
somebody know who could.

00:01:55.400 --> 00:02:01.040
And that would come back to give her a little nip later on in life because I took it to

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:03.120
heart.

00:02:03.120 --> 00:02:06.120
So grew up, it was me, my mom and dad.

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:10.280
I have two older brothers and an older sister.

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:18.760
And when I say older, 14, 20, 25 years between me and my siblings, I was a surprise.

00:02:18.760 --> 00:02:25.640
My mother used to say she thought she had gas.

00:02:25.640 --> 00:02:31.440
So grew up and I went to Catholic schools.

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:33.880
My mother was from Barbados.

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:39.240
And so I went to Saint-Threnda Bar Elementary School, San Ignatius College Prep.

00:02:39.240 --> 00:02:43.680
On both all on the West Side of Chicago, I was going to be a physicist.

00:02:43.680 --> 00:02:47.720
I was a, I love math and science.

00:02:47.720 --> 00:02:52.360
And that was my dream, was to be a physicist and to be an astronaut.

00:02:52.360 --> 00:02:55.640
I became a revolutionary.

00:02:55.640 --> 00:02:57.560
Just a little bit of a D2.

00:02:57.560 --> 00:03:04.480
But all behind that idea of my mom, you see something wrong, you should do something

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:05.480
about it.

00:03:05.480 --> 00:03:12.920
And we got the newspapers, we got, at one point we got the sun times, the tribune, the daily

00:03:12.920 --> 00:03:16.680
news, and the Chicago defender.

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:18.760
So we were well read.

00:03:18.760 --> 00:03:23.760
And so I had an awareness of, as the civil rights movement grew and developed, I had an

00:03:23.760 --> 00:03:27.560
awareness of it from reading the paper.

00:03:27.560 --> 00:03:34.920
Watching the court seeing things on the news, seeing all these activities going on.

00:03:34.920 --> 00:03:39.760
But then there's the things that happen to you.

00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:48.600
We were put to West Side of Chicago near area of Chicago called Cicero.

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:50.960
Cicero is one of those sundown areas.

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:54.880
If you were black, don't have your butt in Cicero after sundown.

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:58.120
You would be hurt, you could be killed.

00:03:58.120 --> 00:04:00.080
And these are things that you grew up knowing.

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:01.320
Yeah, yeah.

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:04.520
Or you sort of knew those things.

00:04:04.520 --> 00:04:09.720
And at the same time, as a kid, I remember me and a buddy, we rode our bike.

00:04:09.720 --> 00:04:12.680
We had bicycles in Cicero.

00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:17.480
In it, we needed some air and tires or something like that and stopped at a gas station to put

00:04:17.480 --> 00:04:18.480
air in the tire.

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:20.520
Next thing you know, there's water.

00:04:20.520 --> 00:04:24.640
Somebody's holding us and get us out of the area.

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:29.160
But the incident that was the real kicker for me, I was in a boy scouts.

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:31.600
And as boy scouts, you're trying to get married badges.

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:36.240
So one day, me and three of my friends, we wanted to get our cycling married badges.

00:04:36.240 --> 00:04:42.320
So we left our area around 13th and Avis, 13th of Pulaski was the major street.

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:46.520
And we were going to ride out past Cresswood, Illinois.

00:04:46.520 --> 00:04:51.160
And we figured that would give us the necessary mileage to get our cycling married badges.

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:57.560
So we're riding, riding, and on our way back, we stopped at this water fountain across

00:04:57.560 --> 00:05:03.280
the street from a little, a little league game that was going on.

00:05:03.280 --> 00:05:05.520
So one by one, we stopped at a water fountain.

00:05:05.520 --> 00:05:11.080
And the last one, and I'm there trying to guzzle all the water in the earth.

00:05:11.080 --> 00:05:16.000
And all of a sudden, I become aware of my friends because as each one drinks, they would

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:17.000
ride on.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:21.480
All of a sudden, I look up and they're waving at me and pointing and yelling.

00:05:21.480 --> 00:05:25.000
And I look, the little league game had stopped.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:27.960
And the stands and the feel had emptied.

00:05:27.960 --> 00:05:31.000
And this is an all white scenario.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:32.640
And they're all running.

00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:37.960
And I still have this image of this woman, white woman, couldn't have been much more than

00:05:37.960 --> 00:05:44.000
five feet tall, running and calling me everything but a child of God with, I know a brick or

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.680
a ball or a bat or something in her hand.

00:05:47.680 --> 00:05:51.080
I rode real fast, caught it with my friends past them.

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:57.600
Now the thing that I find interesting, I don't think I ever told my parents about that.

00:05:57.600 --> 00:05:58.600
Right?

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:02.480
Because that was the way things were.

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:08.200
And we got away, we went on about a business and life went on.

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:14.600
And then later, I was in high school, maybe Southmore year.

00:06:14.600 --> 00:06:22.320
And me and a buddy went to a party on the South Side of Chicago over in the hood.

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:26.320
We walked into this project, a high rise project.

00:06:26.320 --> 00:06:30.160
And we walked into this building, passed these guys and we turned the corner where we thought

00:06:30.160 --> 00:06:33.120
the elevator was, did it?

00:06:33.120 --> 00:06:35.800
Turn around, there's these guys, this gang.

00:06:35.800 --> 00:06:39.280
And they proceeded to beat the snout out of us for however long.

00:06:39.280 --> 00:06:41.600
They literally beat us until they got tired.

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:47.200
Now at one point, the guys who were kicking my butt, kicked my butt out onto the street.

00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:49.520
I guess they wanted some fresh air.

00:06:49.520 --> 00:06:56.120
And at one point, the guy is going to shoot me.

00:06:56.120 --> 00:06:58.080
Because everybody else is like, they're literally tired.

00:06:58.080 --> 00:07:03.840
I'm laying face down the ground, he pulls me up by the, that puts a gun to my head and

00:07:03.840 --> 00:07:04.840
pulls the trigger.

00:07:04.840 --> 00:07:08.120
And this girl, to my mind and angel, snatched it.

00:07:08.120 --> 00:07:09.440
No Johnny, don't do it.

00:07:09.440 --> 00:07:11.720
Snatched his hand.

00:07:11.720 --> 00:07:13.360
And so he pissed away from me.

00:07:13.360 --> 00:07:18.960
And at that point in time, Pistol would be bullet in the head, Pistol would be in the school.

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:23.280
So he tells me to run and I can't run, I can't even stand up, but I crawl real fast.

00:07:23.280 --> 00:07:26.280
Not even fast, just crawl away.

00:07:26.280 --> 00:07:27.600
My friend is still in the building.

00:07:27.600 --> 00:07:29.600
I don't know what's going on with my friend.

00:07:29.600 --> 00:07:33.640
I see a police car stopped at a light and I stagger over to the car.

00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:39.000
Now at this point, I'm bleeding, I'm starting to swell up and I stagger over to the car

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:41.200
and frantically tell him what's happened.

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:45.240
And he looks at me and says, so, white car.

00:07:45.240 --> 00:07:49.160
So I get into the police car because this is what's supposed to happen.

00:07:49.160 --> 00:07:50.880
He's supposed to help me.

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:55.720
And I tell him where to go and he goes, pulls up a front of the building and tells me to

00:07:55.720 --> 00:08:01.080
get out of the car and go into the building and find my friend.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:04.560
Meanwhile the remnants of the gang are sitting outside the building.

00:08:04.560 --> 00:08:05.560
They see me.

00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:10.280
They get up and they're coming to the police car to extract me and finish what they started.

00:08:10.280 --> 00:08:12.840
I said, look, arrest me, take me away from here.

00:08:12.840 --> 00:08:17.880
So he took me to the local police station, which was only a block of two ways I recall.

00:08:17.880 --> 00:08:19.640
So I'm thinking this is an adoration.

00:08:19.640 --> 00:08:23.640
So I go into the police station and I never even get a chance to say anything.

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:26.160
Now I'm really swelling up.

00:08:26.160 --> 00:08:30.480
And the cops all white start laughing when I walk in.

00:08:30.480 --> 00:08:35.520
Now my friend had managed to get in somebody's apartment and he called his mom and we met

00:08:35.520 --> 00:08:40.360
up at the police station and went to the hospital and he got stitches and stuff like that.

00:08:40.920 --> 00:08:46.720
That was my personal wake up call.

00:08:46.720 --> 00:08:52.960
And then I became involved in the youth wing of the NAACP.

00:08:52.960 --> 00:08:57.360
Me and my buddy Tyler, we started a black student organization to say,

00:08:57.360 --> 00:09:01.400
because sitting nation is like this very prestigious college prep.

00:09:01.400 --> 00:09:08.200
95% white on Roosevelt Road in the black community right across from some projects.

00:09:08.200 --> 00:09:09.800
But there was no dynamic.

00:09:09.800 --> 00:09:10.800
There was no interaction.

00:09:10.800 --> 00:09:13.800
And was your street in neighborhood, actually, African American?

00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:14.800
All black.

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:15.800
All black, by the way.

00:09:15.800 --> 00:09:19.800
So and then you go to school during the day of this totally different environment.

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:22.880
Yeah, totally different environment, totally different environment.

00:09:22.880 --> 00:09:26.720
And it's having its own issues that we have to deal with.

00:09:26.720 --> 00:09:37.600
Because a lot of the hostility comes is because people don't have familiarity and people react

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:40.840
based on stereotypes.

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:44.600
And that was the kind of thing that we were constantly confronting.

00:09:44.600 --> 00:09:46.600
Had standing nation has ever had a black student club?

00:09:46.600 --> 00:09:47.600
No.

00:09:47.600 --> 00:09:50.600
How did they react when you wanted to do this?

00:09:50.600 --> 00:09:53.280
Well, actually, it's interesting.

00:09:53.280 --> 00:10:02.000
At first, there was interest because, you know, Jesuits have a history of raising, raising

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:09.000
and cane within the church and fighting for and starting the Mexican revolution of

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:12.800
1810, Hidalgo.

00:10:12.800 --> 00:10:16.240
As I think he was a Jesuit that helped kick that off.

00:10:16.240 --> 00:10:18.520
And I know there were other Jesuits involved.

00:10:18.520 --> 00:10:24.280
So one of the things they arranged, the school arranged, there was a panel.

00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:29.000
It would be two or three black guys and one white guy sometime.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:34.960
And we would go to other Catholic schools in the area and have discussions about race

00:10:34.960 --> 00:10:36.200
relations.

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:43.800
So initially, you know, it was supported to a degree.

00:10:43.800 --> 00:10:46.000
And then what are the years here that's been passed over?

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:47.000
Let's see, I started.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:52.000
I was in Nacious from 65 until I got kicked out in March of 69.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.160
That would have been my senior year.

00:10:54.160 --> 00:10:55.160
But that's a good story.

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:56.160
I'll cover.

00:10:56.160 --> 00:10:56.960
We'll come back to that.

00:10:56.960 --> 00:10:58.960
So this is taking place.

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:02.160
So 65, 66 was my freshman year.

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:08.400
So 66, 67 is when we started this organization there about.

00:11:08.400 --> 00:11:11.440
And we would have meetings.

00:11:11.440 --> 00:11:12.440
We would have discussions.

00:11:12.440 --> 00:11:15.760
We would read books and what have you.

00:11:15.760 --> 00:11:24.440
And then as was happening at that time, black student organizations in schools, high schools

00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:27.760
and colleges had a list of demands.

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:31.760
And we wanted black studies.

00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:43.560
Black history at that time was Booker T. Washington and slavery and not even then Harriet Tubman

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:44.560
so much.

00:11:44.560 --> 00:11:47.280
But it was very, that was it.

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:49.080
So we wanted black studies.

00:11:49.080 --> 00:11:51.160
We wanted outreach community.

00:11:51.160 --> 00:11:54.800
We wanted more minority students in the school.

00:11:54.800 --> 00:12:00.400
So if we submit our little list of demands, they basically said, get out of here.

00:12:00.400 --> 00:12:02.600
So we organized a walk out.

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:07.600
And this was a big thing at the school because this is a school where judges and folks sent

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:08.600
their kids.

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:09.960
So it was a big to do.

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:12.880
So we let this walk out.

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:18.880
And the day of the walk out, there was press.

00:12:18.880 --> 00:12:24.680
My mother found out about this on the news that evening.

00:12:24.680 --> 00:12:25.680
I came home.

00:12:25.680 --> 00:12:27.840
Fortunately, my father worked the graveyard shift.

00:12:27.840 --> 00:12:28.840
He wasn't home.

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:32.920
Otherwise, we might not be having this conversation now.

00:12:32.920 --> 00:12:38.160
So I came home and my mother was sitting there with my brother and one of my brothers and

00:12:38.160 --> 00:12:42.640
my sister crying because she just seen this and she knew there are consequences.

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:49.360
Because it caused more to go to this high school than to some of the local colleges.

00:12:49.360 --> 00:12:50.360
And they had invested a lot.

00:12:50.360 --> 00:12:52.480
I was going to be the first one of my family to go to college.

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:55.320
And I come in right on.

00:12:55.320 --> 00:13:00.400
And my brother decided to fill in for my dad and he burst into the room.

00:13:00.400 --> 00:13:05.120
He was going to kick my butt and I started talking until he listened.

00:13:05.120 --> 00:13:08.440
I had done what my mother had taught me to do.

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:13.560
But in time, she and my father both came to understand that.

00:13:13.560 --> 00:13:19.320
So the next day, we went back to the school and we were informed.

00:13:19.320 --> 00:13:23.560
My father took me to school and we were informed by myself and Tyler.

00:13:23.560 --> 00:13:26.000
We had been expelled from the school.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.760
And that was the end of my high school career.

00:13:29.760 --> 00:13:32.440
Now I'm going to just sort of, here's the thing.

00:13:32.440 --> 00:13:35.680
It's an amazing story.

00:13:35.680 --> 00:13:37.880
We went on where our lives.

00:13:37.880 --> 00:13:41.400
I became, but we both became members of the Black Panther Party.

00:13:41.400 --> 00:13:45.720
And eventually, after the party, he works for unions.

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:49.600
I did a variety of things.

00:13:49.600 --> 00:13:55.720
30 odd years later, we get contacted by one of our classmates, Greg Myers.

00:13:55.720 --> 00:14:03.240
And he said, Mac, we're going to get the school to apologize and give you your high school diploma.

00:14:03.240 --> 00:14:06.800
And 39 years later, that's exactly what happened.

00:14:06.800 --> 00:14:11.880
He had put together this movement, reaching out to just about every Black student who had

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:15.640
ever gone to the school that was still alive.

00:14:15.640 --> 00:14:19.720
And the school apologized and gave us a high school diploma.

00:14:19.720 --> 00:14:20.720
It's amazing.

00:14:20.720 --> 00:14:21.720
Yeah.

00:14:21.720 --> 00:14:24.760
What was really cute is that, did you go back to get it?

00:14:24.760 --> 00:14:26.560
Yeah, they flew us in.

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:27.560
They flew us in.

00:14:27.560 --> 00:14:29.520
They had a big event over 200 people.

00:14:29.520 --> 00:14:31.000
They had it at the school.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:35.160
We got accommodations from the mayor and two members of the U.S. Congress.

00:14:35.160 --> 00:14:38.920
But the thing that I find the cutest is one of Gary's granddaughters had to be about

00:14:38.920 --> 00:14:40.880
five years old set.

00:14:40.880 --> 00:14:43.080
Granddaddy, how come it take you so long?

00:14:43.080 --> 00:14:45.080
Get your diploma.

00:14:45.080 --> 00:14:49.080
And you get a good story.

00:14:49.080 --> 00:14:50.080
Oh, yeah.

00:14:50.080 --> 00:14:51.080
Yeah, that's amazing.

00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:59.080
I wanted to ask about, because those times in Chicago, where you, I mean, you guys were

00:14:59.080 --> 00:15:03.400
in school, but were you aware of King coming to town and organizing?

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:04.400
Oh, yeah.

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:05.400
Really?

00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:06.400
Okay.

00:15:06.400 --> 00:15:08.000
When he came, he stayed around the corner.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.840
In fact, my buddy Tyler, he got to see him.

00:15:11.840 --> 00:15:15.720
Got to see him, because he was right across from Douglas Park.

00:15:15.720 --> 00:15:16.720
He was on Hamlin.

00:15:16.720 --> 00:15:18.320
He stayed on Hamlin.

00:15:18.320 --> 00:15:30.880
And right across from Douglas Park and Gary was walking from the park towards his house.

00:15:30.880 --> 00:15:36.600
And Dr. King was talking out the windows to some of his staff.

00:15:36.600 --> 00:15:40.000
And he looked up and said, good morning, Dr. King.

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:41.000
Good morning, young man.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:42.200
It was just, yeah.

00:15:42.200 --> 00:15:43.200
Yeah.

00:15:43.200 --> 00:15:44.200
Yeah.

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:52.120
And I remember, I actually do a story about it, how King said, I have dealt with racism

00:15:52.120 --> 00:15:53.920
throughout the South.

00:15:53.920 --> 00:15:58.240
And I ain't seen nothing like racism in Chicago.

00:15:58.240 --> 00:16:05.320
You know, there was a priest who taught racism from the pulpit over in Mayor Daley's

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:06.320
neighborhood.

00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:10.440
I can't remember his name, but I have it somewhere.

00:16:10.440 --> 00:16:17.040
In fact, because I remember while we were in high school, one summer, we had this job,

00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:26.520
and we were going to the, who were in Bridgeport, knocking on doors, trying to sell something.

00:16:26.520 --> 00:16:31.240
Somebody didn't like us.

00:16:31.240 --> 00:16:32.560
So we're doing this.

00:16:32.560 --> 00:16:35.320
We get endorsed land on our face and what have you.

00:16:35.320 --> 00:16:37.960
And then one of our white classmates, this is all through Ignatius.

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:42.360
One of our white classes marked classmates.

00:16:42.360 --> 00:16:43.200
He says, come on.

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:44.200
He drives up.

00:16:44.200 --> 00:16:45.200
Come on, come on.

00:16:45.200 --> 00:16:46.480
Y'all getting the car.

00:16:46.480 --> 00:16:51.000
Because he had overheard this group of white folks saying they're going to ground us up

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:52.840
and do us bodily harm.

00:16:52.840 --> 00:16:53.840
Yeah.

00:16:53.840 --> 00:16:57.880
That was our last date doing that job.

00:16:57.880 --> 00:17:04.920
Yeah, Chicago was still considered the most segregated city on planet earth.

00:17:04.920 --> 00:17:06.760
Very much so.

00:17:06.760 --> 00:17:07.760
Yeah.

00:17:07.760 --> 00:17:13.000
I mean, do you remember there being a change of any kind when King and those folks came

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:15.600
in or there being talk about it or?

00:17:15.600 --> 00:17:16.600
Oh, I remember.

00:17:16.600 --> 00:17:17.600
Yeah, yeah.

00:17:17.600 --> 00:17:26.760
There was with I remember that before the Demons, he was going to be a march.

00:17:26.760 --> 00:17:30.800
Before the march began, King was hit upside the head with a brick.

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:41.120
Before the march began and the level of violence, the level of animosity, he said, he, I mean,

00:17:41.120 --> 00:17:42.480
he'd been holed down.

00:17:42.480 --> 00:17:44.000
He'd been dealing with the clad in the South.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:48.640
You say, I ain't seen nothing like this.

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:52.240
Oh, Chicago.

00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:53.240
So tell me about it.

00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:54.640
So you got kicked out of high school.

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:55.640
Mm-hmm.

00:17:55.640 --> 00:17:56.640
What next?

00:17:56.640 --> 00:18:02.040
Well, then I became a full-time member of the Illinois chapter of the Black Panther Party.

00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:05.760
And when had you first come in contact with the Black Panther Party?

00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:08.000
Well, I'd said I read.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:13.440
And so in, you see, the Party formed in October of 1966.

00:18:13.440 --> 00:18:20.920
And it was, I think, around 67 that they went to the Sacramento Capitol to protest the law,

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:21.920
67-68.

00:18:21.920 --> 00:18:29.640
They went to protest the law that they had been using to bear arms legally.

00:18:29.640 --> 00:18:31.680
And that was in the news.

00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:34.400
I mean, that was an amazing thing.

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:39.960
The pictures of them standing on the Capitol steps with their weapons and the fact that

00:18:39.960 --> 00:18:46.040
they were patrolling the police with their guns and with their law books.

00:18:46.040 --> 00:18:47.040
All right.

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:48.040
So, and I read ramparts.

00:18:48.040 --> 00:18:49.520
I read ramparts magazine.

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:53.120
Among everything I was putting in addition to Ebony and Jet.

00:18:53.120 --> 00:19:01.800
I read ramparts and other magazines and newspapers that dealt with the social dealing with social

00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:02.800
injustice.

00:19:02.800 --> 00:19:06.840
So I had a great awareness of the existence of the Black Panther Party and what they were

00:19:06.840 --> 00:19:08.680
doing out there.

00:19:08.680 --> 00:19:19.880
And then when they came to Chicago in October, October, November of 1968, I got the word

00:19:19.880 --> 00:19:24.680
that there was an office, 2350 West Madison, right in the corner of Western Madison.

00:19:24.680 --> 00:19:30.560
I be lying there for the political education class to find out about the party.

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:35.640
And a guy I knew, a friend of mine, I used to run track when I was in high school.

00:19:35.640 --> 00:19:42.040
And this guy, Billy Che Brooks, who was the Deputy Minister of Education, he ran track

00:19:42.040 --> 00:19:43.040
for Marshall.

00:19:43.040 --> 00:19:44.040
That's how I knew him.

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:47.520
And when I arrived at the office, there he was.

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:53.480
And so I became a part of the education contract, which was quite apropos.

00:19:53.480 --> 00:19:56.200
We talked to political education classes.

00:19:56.200 --> 00:19:57.200
We read.

00:19:57.200 --> 00:19:58.560
We discuss.

00:19:58.560 --> 00:20:01.800
We, there was a reading list.

00:20:01.800 --> 00:20:03.160
Everybody had to read.

00:20:03.160 --> 00:20:05.760
But we had to read everything on a reading list.

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:07.760
And we discussed, have these discussions.

00:20:07.760 --> 00:20:10.880
And then we would leave these political education classes.

00:20:10.880 --> 00:20:14.960
We would sometimes give talks.

00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:21.000
There were times when Fred would send me in his place to a debate or to give a speech,

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:27.160
which was more than a notion because Fred was a phenomenal, phenomenal speaker and a

00:20:27.160 --> 00:20:28.400
leader.

00:20:28.400 --> 00:20:32.480
So those were some of the tasks that I became involved in when I was in the party.

00:20:32.480 --> 00:20:37.600
And when you're talking about Fred, you're talking about Deputy Chairman Fred Hampton,

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:46.800
one of the most amazing, like I said, speakers, a motivator, a leader, and someone who taught

00:20:46.800 --> 00:20:51.720
me the true meaning of commitment, totally committed to this.

00:20:51.720 --> 00:20:57.160
And I mean Fred was, the thing that was so amazing about Fred, Fred was 21 years old when

00:20:57.160 --> 00:20:59.680
he was assassinated.

00:20:59.680 --> 00:21:02.400
But Fred was, as they say, an old soul.

00:21:02.400 --> 00:21:10.480
I mean, in high school, he had been organizing out in Maywood at the various high schools.

00:21:10.480 --> 00:21:13.200
The blacks couldn't swim at the pool.

00:21:13.200 --> 00:21:16.040
Fred said, okay, we got to do something about this.

00:21:16.040 --> 00:21:17.040
That's what he was about.

00:21:17.040 --> 00:21:19.200
He was about doing something about things.

00:21:19.280 --> 00:21:32.360
And he was also someone who was open to learning new things, taking new approaches.

00:21:32.360 --> 00:21:38.360
Friend of mine, when he came to join the Illinois chapter of the Black Panther Party, there's

00:21:38.360 --> 00:21:43.360
the stereotype of the Black Panther Party as being an anti-white organization.

00:21:43.360 --> 00:21:46.440
No, we were anti-injustice.

00:21:46.440 --> 00:21:51.800
And one of the things that made the party dangerous was the idea that we saw beyond this concept

00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:57.760
of race and race being a tool that was used to divide people who should be working together.

00:21:57.760 --> 00:22:02.120
So my friend came up to join the party and it's like, so give me a gun.

00:22:02.120 --> 00:22:04.120
I want to kill some white people.

00:22:04.120 --> 00:22:06.720
And Fred said, no, that's not how we do things.

00:22:06.720 --> 00:22:07.720
All right.

00:22:07.720 --> 00:22:09.400
Here's some literature.

00:22:09.400 --> 00:22:10.400
Take a look at this.

00:22:10.400 --> 00:22:15.560
And if you're still interested, come back, which he did.

00:22:15.560 --> 00:22:22.240
But many people aren't aware of the fact that Fred Hampton and Illinois chapter started

00:22:22.240 --> 00:22:24.480
the Rainbow Coalition.

00:22:24.480 --> 00:22:32.880
Oh, that, we had the Rainbow Coalition, the Black Panther Party, the Young Lords, the Young

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:34.680
Patriots.

00:22:34.680 --> 00:22:38.320
Now people don't know about this.

00:22:38.320 --> 00:22:43.640
The Young Lords had been a Puerto Rican street gang that became political.

00:22:43.640 --> 00:22:49.560
The Young Patriots were poor Appalachian white folks.

00:22:49.560 --> 00:22:56.760
And you can see in American Revolution 2, it's on YouTube, you can see the meeting where

00:22:56.760 --> 00:23:04.040
Bob Lee and Hank Gattis, who are our field secretaries, had gone into this community, into

00:23:04.040 --> 00:23:10.600
the poor Appalachian white community, to talk to these people about why poor whites and

00:23:10.600 --> 00:23:14.120
poor blacks should be working together.

00:23:14.120 --> 00:23:16.040
And there was this meeting.

00:23:16.040 --> 00:23:24.440
And Bob Lee is talking, and at the end of the meeting, this mic, I can't remember, my

00:23:24.440 --> 00:23:26.760
great, my great was the director.

00:23:26.760 --> 00:23:34.120
He interviews this old guy and says, well, what do you think about what the Panther said?

00:23:34.120 --> 00:23:36.360
And I paraphrase it like this.

00:23:36.360 --> 00:23:41.440
But of them black Panthers going for us, I guess we should support them black Panthers.

00:23:41.440 --> 00:23:48.280
And a week later, a week later, Bob Lee was in the area by himself doing some organizing,

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:54.760
and he was stopped and arrested by the police, put it into police car to be taken away.

00:23:54.760 --> 00:23:56.920
Young Patriots saw what happened.

00:23:56.920 --> 00:24:00.400
They saw what happened, and they put the word out.

00:24:00.400 --> 00:24:05.200
Before that police car could go, they came and surrounded it.

00:24:05.200 --> 00:24:11.160
Women and women and children, white men and women and children, and they made the police

00:24:11.160 --> 00:24:14.680
let Bob Lee go.

00:24:14.680 --> 00:24:22.720
Poor whites, black folks working together, that was a dangerous thing for the powers to

00:24:22.720 --> 00:24:24.120
be.

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:27.040
And that outreach started.

00:24:27.040 --> 00:24:32.400
The young Patriots, the young lords, there were other groups that became associated with

00:24:32.400 --> 00:24:33.400
it.

00:24:33.400 --> 00:24:36.720
They started organizing their own breakfast with children programs.

00:24:36.720 --> 00:24:39.840
They started having their own political education classes.

00:24:39.840 --> 00:24:45.400
They started talking about why we should not be fighting with each other, why we should

00:24:45.400 --> 00:24:46.880
be working together.

00:24:46.880 --> 00:24:50.080
Oh, that was a dynamic, and that was inspired by Fred.

00:24:50.080 --> 00:24:54.840
And why was that threatening to the powers to be?

00:24:54.840 --> 00:24:59.080
Dividing Conquer is the oldest tool in the book.

00:24:59.080 --> 00:25:00.640
What do you do?

00:25:00.640 --> 00:25:06.280
Here you have people that should be working together and interco and tel pro.

00:25:06.280 --> 00:25:08.280
All right, interco and tel pro.

00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:09.720
So what do you do?

00:25:09.720 --> 00:25:11.840
You drop.

00:25:11.840 --> 00:25:14.480
You have people drop misinformation.

00:25:14.480 --> 00:25:16.240
Oh, oh, so and so.

00:25:16.240 --> 00:25:23.360
One of the other things that the Black Panther Party was doing was working with the street

00:25:23.360 --> 00:25:29.360
gangs and getting them to stop exploiting the community and it become political.

00:25:29.360 --> 00:25:34.240
At the time, the biggest gang in the country, not just Chicago in the country, was the Black

00:25:34.240 --> 00:25:41.840
Peace Stone Nation, the Black Stone Rangers later called the El Rookins and Fred and Bobby

00:25:41.840 --> 00:25:51.440
Rush had these meetings to try to get them to shift their focus and become political.

00:25:51.440 --> 00:25:58.440
The FBI under the Kelantel Pro program, all of this is when we didn't know at the time

00:25:58.440 --> 00:26:02.400
that William O'Neill, our head of security was the FBI plan.

00:26:02.400 --> 00:26:06.000
But someone would call the Panthers, a writer letter.

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:08.480
Someone would call the Black Peace Stone Nation.

00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:15.200
Yo, yo, so and so, they're trying to set you up to keep us from doing this working together.

00:26:15.200 --> 00:26:16.680
And it almost worked.

00:26:16.680 --> 00:26:17.680
All right.

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:20.960
They did not get to the point they would have liked it.

00:26:20.960 --> 00:26:27.280
But people got to see, we didn't know this thing was happening, but we knew something was

00:26:27.280 --> 00:26:28.600
going on.

00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:29.760
All right.

00:26:29.760 --> 00:26:35.520
Were there other plants or suspicions that there were others?

00:26:35.520 --> 00:26:38.640
So did it kind of work in terms of creating paranoia?

00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:43.840
Well, in a manner of speaking, you had to be.

00:26:43.840 --> 00:26:51.520
Because once we, it was a given that we would be infiltrated.

00:26:51.520 --> 00:26:55.560
It was a given.

00:26:55.560 --> 00:27:02.400
But when you started seeing things happen and then all of a sudden that you have these people

00:27:02.400 --> 00:27:03.880
who are prodding this.

00:27:03.880 --> 00:27:09.640
So a level of justified paranoia was indeed evident.

00:27:09.640 --> 00:27:13.040
And that did ultimately have an effect on the party.

00:27:13.040 --> 00:27:20.760
And in fact, on the movement in general, I like to make reference to this book, The

00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:27.040
Burglary, about the peace activists who broke into the FBI office in media, Pennsylvania,

00:27:27.040 --> 00:27:30.880
March 8, 1971, the night of the Ali Frazier fight.

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:36.400
Because they broke in that night because they knew whether they hoped that that would

00:27:36.400 --> 00:27:39.320
allow them ease and getting into the office.

00:27:39.320 --> 00:27:43.560
Because everybody would be watching the fight and that indeed was the case.

00:27:43.560 --> 00:27:52.400
They are who discovered Coentelpro in one of the files that they took.

00:27:52.400 --> 00:27:56.440
And then we found out all manner of stuff that was going on.

00:27:56.440 --> 00:28:01.440
I mean, oh my goodness.

00:28:01.440 --> 00:28:03.400
I can't remember her name.

00:28:03.400 --> 00:28:08.880
There was an actress here in LA who was the supporter of the party.

00:28:08.880 --> 00:28:11.560
She would do fun races and what have you.

00:28:11.560 --> 00:28:17.400
Jay Guhuva ordered the FBI office here in LA to neutralize her.

00:28:17.400 --> 00:28:18.400
They started a rumor.

00:28:18.400 --> 00:28:19.400
She was pregnant.

00:28:19.400 --> 00:28:20.400
She was married.

00:28:20.400 --> 00:28:27.120
They started a rumor that the baby wasn't her husband's and the baby died.

00:28:27.120 --> 00:28:30.400
The woman committed suicide.

00:28:30.400 --> 00:28:41.600
The LA FBI office was compensated for having successfully destroyed this woman's life.

00:28:41.600 --> 00:28:42.600
Okay.

00:28:42.600 --> 00:28:43.600
Oh.

00:28:43.600 --> 00:28:44.600
Yeah.

00:28:44.600 --> 00:28:45.600
Yeah.

00:28:45.600 --> 00:28:48.800
So that's the kind of thing.

00:28:48.800 --> 00:28:50.200
And again, we didn't know.

00:28:50.200 --> 00:28:52.640
Like I said, again, we knew but we didn't know.

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:57.880
But our approach was we are going to keep doing positive stuff.

00:28:57.880 --> 00:29:01.280
We are going to keep serving the people and helping the people.

00:29:01.280 --> 00:29:06.420
Thus the breakfast program, the free medical clinics, which Jay Guhuva said that the

00:29:06.420 --> 00:29:10.480
most dangerous thing we did was the breakfast for children program because the government

00:29:10.480 --> 00:29:13.480
wasn't feeding any children to that particular point in time.

00:29:13.480 --> 00:29:22.200
In fact, the subsequent programs they came were essentially the government saying, okay,

00:29:22.200 --> 00:29:24.320
we can't have these pastors showing us out.

00:29:24.320 --> 00:29:25.320
We call it feed them.

00:29:25.320 --> 00:29:26.320
Head start.

00:29:26.320 --> 00:29:27.320
Yeah.

00:29:28.320 --> 00:29:30.400
So what other programs?

00:29:30.400 --> 00:29:33.120
So and it is very interesting.

00:29:33.120 --> 00:29:38.760
At the 40th anniversary of the Black Panther Party, I went, I was in Oakland and it was a

00:29:38.760 --> 00:29:41.840
report by people from other chapters.

00:29:41.840 --> 00:29:49.560
And it was very interesting because at the time we were immersed in wherever we were.

00:29:49.560 --> 00:29:50.560
All right.

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:51.560
There was the national stuff.

00:29:51.560 --> 00:29:52.560
There was the local stuff.

00:29:52.560 --> 00:29:53.560
You got the paper.

00:29:53.560 --> 00:29:55.000
You read about stuff going on.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:29:59.680
But unless you were at some other, you know, visiting some other place, you didn't know

00:29:59.680 --> 00:30:02.840
what was going on.

00:30:02.840 --> 00:30:04.800
So in Illinois, we had the...

